Below is the definition of “Material Adverse Effect” as provided in the Acquisition Agreement between Magic AcquireCo, Inc. and The Michaels Companies, Inc. (all emphasis added and exclusions numbered as in the original):

“Material Adverse Effect” means an event, occurrence, development, circumstance, change or effect that has a material adverse effect on the condition (financial or otherwise), business, assets or results of operations of the Company and its Subsidiaries, taken as a whole, excluding any effect resulting from:

  1.  Changes in the financial, securities, credit, debt, banking or other capital markets or conditions (including changes therein) or foreign or domestic economic, financial, regulatory, legislative, political or social conditions (including changes therein);
  2.  Changes or conditions generally affecting the industry in which the Company and its Subsidiaries operate or to the industries to which they sell their products and services, including changes in interest and exchange rates or commodity pricing, in any relevant jurisdiction;
  3.  Geopolitical conditions, hostilities, acts of war, tariffs, trade wars, transportation delays (including work stoppages or port closures), cyber‑attacks, sabotage, civil unrest, terrorism or other occurrences of instability;
  4.  (1) Plagues, pandemics (including SARS‑CoV‑2/COVID‑19) or other disease outbreaks or (2) hurricanes, tornadoes, floods, earthquakes or other natural or man‑made disasters or force majeure events;
  5.  Any quarantine, “shelter in place,” “stay at home,” social distancing, shutdown, closure or similar laws, directives or guidelines relating to COVID‑19 (the “COVID‑19 Measures”);
  6.  Changes or prospective changes in Applicable Law, Tax or GAAP (or their interpretation) on or after the date of the Agreement;
  7.  Failure by the Company or any Subsidiary to meet internal or published projections, forecasts or guidance, or changes in the market price or trading volume of the Company’s securities or its credit rating (subject to taking into account underlying facts not otherwise excluded);
  8.  Seasonal fluctuations consistent with historical patterns;
  9.  The identity of, or any facts or circumstances relating to, Parent, Merger Subsidiary or their Affiliates;
  10.  The negotiation, announcement, pendency or consummation of the Transactions (including any loss or change in relationships with counterparties), except to the extent related to any breach of a Material Contract representation under Section 4.04;
  11.  Any litigation, suit or proceeding concerning this Agreement or the transactions contemplated hereby or by the Offer Documents (including fiduciary‑duty or disclosure claims); and
  12.  (1) Any action taken by the Company or a Subsidiary at the written request or with the written consent of Parent or Merger Subsidiary or (2) compliance with, or failure to take actions prohibited by, the express terms of this Agreement.

Except that, with respect to clauses (ii) through (vi) above, any effect that is materially disproportionate to the impact on other participants in the same industry may be taken into account when determining whether a Material Adverse Effect has occurred.  

(Source: Definition of “Material Adverse Effect” in the provided Acquisition Agreement context)

Below is the Agreement’s definition of “Company Material Adverse Effect,” which is the operative “Material Adverse Effect” concept for HMS Holdings Corp. (the “Company”).1

1. General Definition  
“Company Material Adverse Effect” means any event, change, effect, fact, circumstance, development, condition or occurrence (each an “Effect”) that either:  
  a. prevents or materially impairs the ability of the Company to consummate the Transactions; or  
  b. has had, or would reasonably be expected to have, a material adverse effect on the results of operations or financial condition of the Acquired Companies, taken as a whole;  

2. Carve‑Outs—Non‑Excludable Effects  
Notwithstanding clause (1.b), none of the following, alone or in combination, shall be deemed to constitute a “Company Material Adverse Effect” (nor be taken into account in determining whether one has occurred), except to the extent such matters “disproportionately impact the Acquired Companies (taken as a whole) relative to other businesses in the industries in which the Acquired Companies operate” (applicable to clauses (i), (ii), (iii), (iv), (v) and (ix) only):  
  (i) Changes in Applicable Law, GAAP or any accounting standards or interpretations thereof;  
  (ii) General economic, political or business conditions, acts of terrorism, epidemics or pandemics (including COVID‑19), disease outbreaks or changes in geopolitical conditions (including war, armed hostilities or governmental responses thereto);  
  (iii) Financial and capital market conditions, including interest‑rate and currency‑exchange fluctuations;  
  (iv) Seasonal fluctuations in the business of the Acquired Companies;  
  (v) Any change generally affecting the industries in which the Acquired Companies operate;  
  (vi) The negotiation, entry into or announcement of this Agreement or the Transactions (including related stockholder or derivative litigation or damage to reputation), provided that this carve‑out does not apply to references to “Company Material Adverse Effect” in the Company’s reps and warranties in Sections 4.02, 4.03, 4.04 and 4.16(h);  
  (vii) Compliance with the terms of this Agreement;  
  (viii) Actions expressly required or permitted by this Agreement, or taken at Parent’s written request;  
  (ix) Acts of God or natural disasters;  
  (x) Changes in the price or trading volume of the Company’s securities or financial instruments (standing alone), provided the underlying cause is not otherwise excluded;  
  (xi) Failure to meet internal or published projections, estimates or forecasts (standing alone), provided the underlying cause is not otherwise excluded;  
  (xii) For purposes of Section 8.02(c): (A) matters disclosed in the Company Disclosure Letter; or (B) disclosures in the Company SEC Documents that modify an Article IV representation or warranty, to the extent reasonably foreseeable and apparent on the face of the disclosure as of the date hereof.  

Source: Context, “Company Material Adverse Effect” definition.
